<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most People Get Wrong</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>They overcomplicate storage.</strong> Simple systems are easier to maintain and use.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>They ignore moisture control.</strong> Even well-organized seeds can degrade if stored improperly.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>They prioritize storage over access.</strong> If seeds are hard to find, they are less likely to be used effectively.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Do</h2>

  <p>
    Start with a simple, organized storage system like a photo case that keeps seeds visible and protected. Focus on consistency rather than complexity.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    The best system is the one you actually use.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    The best seed storage box is one that keeps seeds dry, organized, and easy to access throughout the season.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Good storage supports better planting decisions.
  </p>
</section>